Basics

Setting up and reading in data

The working directory

A quick reminder of what it is and how to set it…

  • The working directory is a default location that R will use to looks for files. It is just a folder on your computer.

  • If you don't set the working directory, R will do it for you. This is probably not the folder you want to use.

  • YOU should set the working directory EVERY TIME you start R/RStudio. Setting your working directory should be the first thing you do.

  • Do not do this using R code in your script. Instead, do it using the RStudio menu system (there are other ways, don't use them).



Set your working directory now using: Session > Set Working Directory > Choose Directory…

Starting a new script

Start a new script using: File > New File… > R Script

Then add the following to the beginning of your script:

# clear the workspace (aka R's 'brain')
rm(list = ls())

Can you remember what this does? Why is it a good idea always include it?

This script hasn't been saved. Do that now…

Packages

Packages extend what base R can do. Two things have to happen before you can actually use the functions in a package:

  1. You have to install it. This is a "do once" operation. After a package is installed you can restart R and it is still installed.

  2. You have to load and attach it. This is a "do every time" operation. You have to load and attach the package every time you start a new session (= open R).




A mobile phone App analogy:

  • installing a package <=> getting an App from an App store

  • loading and attaching a package <=> opening the App on your phone

Accessing a package

  1. We install a package with the install.packages function

  2. We load and attach an installed package with the library function

Remember!

  • Never use install.packages inside your scripts! You don't want to reinstall a package every time you plan to use it.

  • You can install a package via the Packages tab in RStudio. Use this if you don't like using install.packages.

We need dplyr abd ggplot2…

Step 1. Install dplyr abd ggplot2

Go to the Packages tab in RStudio (bottom right pane by default) and click the 'Install' button. Type the following: dplyr, ggplot2… and click the 'Install' button.

Step 2. Place the following into your script, and then submit it to the Console:

library("dplyr")
library("ggplot2")

Remember: you don't have to repeat 'Step 1' in every new R session

Data in R

Vectors, data frames, 'tibbles', etc.

Two views of data frames

The first view: Data frames are a collection of vectors. These may be different types (numeric, character, others), but they must all be the same length.

The second view: Data frames are table-like objects. Take another look at our simple data frame. This clearly has rows and columns.

Data frames are central to data analysis in R. We can think of each vector as corresponding to a statistical variable that we want to analyse. Almost every function we will learn about this year works with data stored in a data frame.

'Tibbles'

Er, what the @^$£ is a 'tibble'?… They were called a 'tbl' last year (pronounced 'table'). Basically, a special version of the data frame. dplyr tends to produce them. We can convert if we need to, e.g.

tbl_df(storms)        # <- the old way (deprecated)
# or
as_data_frame(storms) # <- the new way

Add this to your script now…

storms <- as_data_frame(storms)

The only thing you really need to be aware of is that a tibble is printed to the Console more compactly than a data frame.

Extracting a vector (i.e. a column)

We can extract a vector from a data frame in a few different ways:

  • Using the name and the $ operator
storms$name
  • Using the name and the [[ ]] operator
  • Using the position and the [[ ]] operator

We'll just use the $ method, and we won't need it often.

Getting help

The many different routes

Built in 'help' files

We do the following:

?name_of_a_useful_function

Help files are really documentation files:

  • Description
  • Usage
  • Arguments
  • Details
  • References
  • Examples <– This is often the most useful part

Better options for help are the internet (e.g. google, stack overflow), books and those cheat sheets…

The dplyr package

Manipulating data

The five key verbs

****dplyr** has five main "verbs", each of which corresponds to a function:**

  • select: Extract a subset of variables
  • filter: Extract a subset of rows
  • arrange: Reorder rows
  • mutate: Construct new variables
  • summarise: Calculate information about groups

(+ a few other important functions that we need too, e.g. slice, rename, and most important of all, group_by)


**It is useful to classify the verbs according to what they work on:__

  • observations (rows): filter & slice & arrange
  • variables (columns): select & rename & mutate

(This classification only works if your data are tidy)

Using filter

Reminder: comparing values

Use relational operators to compare the elements of vectors:

  • x < y: is x less than y?
  • x > y: is x greater than y?
  • x <= y: is x less than or equal to y?
  • x >= y: is x greater than or equal to y?
  • x == y: is x equal to y?
  • x != y: is x not equal to y?

Using filter

Use filter to select a subset of rows for further analysis based on the result(s) of one or more comparisons. Using filter looks like this:

filter(data, <expression>)

Arguments

  • data: the name of a data frame or tibble object
  • <expression>: logical comparison involving variables in data

Comments

The <expression> typically uses a combination of relational (e.g. < and ==) operators (+ maybe logical (e.g. & and |) operators)

Using select

We use select to to extract a subset of variables for further analysis. Using select looks like this:

select(data, Variable1, Variable2, ...)

Arguments

  • data: the name of a data frame or tibble object
  • VariableX: the names of one or more variables in data

Exercise

Using mutate

Use mutate to add derived variables. This is how we use mutate:

mutate(data, NewVar = <expression>, ...)

Arguments

  • data: the name of a data frame or tibble object
  • NewVar: name of a new variable to create
  • <expression>: an expression that references variables in data

Comments

  • The <expression> that appears on the right hand side of the = can be any valid R expression that uses variables in data.
  • You can use more than one NewVar = <expression> at a time (seperated by ,) if you need to construct several new variables.

The dplyr package

Piping operations and summarising data

Using the 'pipe' %>%

The dplyr package inmports a special operator, called 'the pipe'. It looks like this: %>%. This allows us to chain together a sequence of operations, reading from left to right and top to bottom. For example, take a look at this sequence of calculations:

x <- 10
x <- sqrt(x)
round(x, 2)
## [1] 3.16

The piped version looks like this

10 %>% sqrt() %>% round(2)
## [1] 3.16

Exercise

Making a new variable

See if you can use the %>% to construct a pipeline that filters, selects, and then mutates the storms data, using the same criteria as were used in each of the last three exercises.

storms %>% 
  filter(type == "Hurricane", year >= 1997) %>% 
  select(name, year, pressure) %>% 
  mutate(pressure_Pa = 100 * pressure)
## # A tibble: 501 × 4
##      name  year pressure pressure_Pa
##    <fctr> <int>    <int>       <dbl>
## 1    Bill  1997      987       98700
## 2    Bill  1997      987       98700
## 3   Danny  1997      992       99200
## 4   Danny  1997      990       99000
## 5   Danny  1997      988       98800
## 6   Danny  1997      984       98400
## 7   Danny  1997      987       98700
## 8   Danny  1997      984       98400
## 9   Danny  1997      986       98600
## 10  Erika  1997      999       99900
## # ... with 491 more rows

Warning!

Remember that if you want to actually use the result of a piped set of operations, you have to assign a name to the result, e.g.

processed_storms <- 
  storms %>% 
  filter(type == "Hurricane", year >= 1997) %>% 
  select(name, year, pressure) %>% 
  mutate(pressure_Pa = 100 * pressure)

Using summarise

We use summarise to calculate summaries of variables. This is how we use summarise:

summarise(data, SummaryVar = <expression>, ...)

Arguments

  • data: the name of a data frame or tibble object
  • SummaryVar: name of your summary variable
  • <expression>: an expression that references variables in data

Comments

  • The <expression> that appears on the right hand side of the = can be any valid R expression that uses variables in data. However, <expression> must return a single value (e.g. mean(), var(), sd(), n() are all fine).
  • Although summarise looks a lot like mutate, it is designed to construct a completely new, much smaller, dataset containing summaries of one or more variables.
  • You may use more than one SummaryStat = <expression> at a time (seperated by ,) if you need to construct several summaries.

Using group_by

Use group_by to add grouping information to a tibble or data frame. This is how we use group_by:

group_by(data, GroupVar1, GroupVar2, ...)

Arguments

  • data: the name of a data frame or tibble object
  • GroupVar: name of grouping variable(s)

Comments

  • The group_by function does not do anything more than add grouping information to the input. It is only useful when used with another function (e.g summarise).
  • Using group_by with summarise enables us to calculate numerical summaries on a per group basis.

Exercise

Using group_by to group by more than one variable

You're going to use group_by and summarise together, along with the pipe (%>%) in this exercise. Use the group_by and summarise functions on the storms dataset to calculate the minimum and maximum wind speed associated with each month. Call the summary variables min_speed and max_speed.

Hint: You need to know the names of the two functions that calculate the minimum and maximum of a numeric vector.

storms %>% 
  group_by(month) %>%
  summarise(min_speed = min(wind), max_speed = max(wind))

Overview of ggplot2

The grammar of graphics

Key concepts

You need to wrap your head around a few ideas to start using ggplot2 effectively:

  • layers: We build ggplot2 objects by adding one or more layers together. We can do this in a stepwise way, only plotting the object when we are ready. Each layer needs things like data, aesthetics, geometric objects, etc
  • aesthetics: The word aesthetics refers to the information in a plot. For example, the variables associated with: the x and y axes, point colours, line types, etc. We specify this using the aes function.
  • geometric objects: Geometric objects ("geoms") determine how the information is displayed. For example, will it be a scatter plot or a bar plot? We can specify geoms by adding a layer via functions beginning with geom_.

We build up a plot by combining different functions using the + operator. This has nothing to do with numeric addition!

Example: Scatter plots

Quick remoind of how all this works:

We don't have to build a plot object up in separate steps and then explicitly "print"" it to the Console. If we just want to make th eplot in one go we can do it like this:

ggplot(storms, aes(x = pressure, y = wind)) + 
  geom_point(colour = "purple") + 
  labs(x = "Pressure (mbar)", y = "Wind speed (km/hr)")

Exercise

What are histograms and dot plots?

We use histograms and dot plots to understand the distribution of a variable. They summarise the number of observations occuring in a contiguous series of bins. Use geom_histogram to construct a histogram and geom_dotplot. Here is an example:

See if you can make that plot…

Answer

ggplot(storms, aes(x = pressure)) + 
  geom_histogram(colour = "darkgrey", fill = "grey", binwidth=10) + 
  labs(x = "Pressure", y = "Count")

Miscellaneous 'stuff'

  • R does not change things 'in place'. You have to use assignment <- ('gets')…

  • Scientific notation in R looks like this: 1e-16. That is R-speak for \(1.0 \ times 10^{-16}\), i.e. a very small number.

  • Don;t forget the basics, e.g. mean(), var(), sd(), n()

  • Keyboard shortcuts are useful. We really like 'Alt-Underscore' (<-) and 'Ctrl-Shift-M' (%>%).
